### 3.3 Justified Row Layouts

If columns let portrait photos dominate, a justified row layout leans the other way: photos in each row share the same height, and the row is scaled so its contents span the full container width. In practice this means every photo keeps its aspect ratio, but widths vary so the row fills the line.

![Justified row layout](./assets/justified.svg "Photos in each row share the same height, but row heights and number of photos per row vary")

Because width maps directly to area in this scheme, wide images tend to dominate. A single landscape or panorama can occupy as much visual weight as several portraits combined — the same effect that made portraits stand out in the column layout now applies to landscapes here.

![Flickr justified layout](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/flickr-justified.avif "Flickr's justified layout — the landscape takes more space than two portraits combined")

That dominance shapes the layout's rhythm. Justified rows create strong horizontal leading lines: the aligned gaps between rows repeat across the page, producing a unidirectional rhythm. When most of your collection is landscape-oriented, this layout can actually reinforce the work rather than fight it.

![Justified layout with leading lines](./assets/justified-leading-lines.svg "Strong horizontal leading lines from aligned row gaps")

However, the rhythm is softer than in strict column layouts because row heights change with their contents. Narrower viewports fit fewer photos per row, so row heights vary more and the pattern reads less mechanical. This variation can make the layout feel more organic even while preserving aspect ratios.

A practical downside: justified rows require JavaScript, because you need to measure image dimensions and compute scale factors so each row fills the container while keeping consistent heights. If you want a ready-made solution, [justified-layout library](https://github.com/flickr/justified-layout) is a solid starting point.

As a side note, CSS Grid's [experimental masonry feature](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_Grid_Layout/Masonry_Layout) may one day provide similar, more automatic arrangements without JS, but [browser support remains limited](https://caniuse.com/?search=masonry) as of late 2025.

So, like the other approaches we've seen, justified rows trade one bias for another — they favor wide formats while preserving compositions. What if we tried something different?

